,"France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Corbeil","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Fernand, Jean-Louis, Armand, Fernande, Gilles, Hugues, Huguette, Jean Pierre, Jean-Baptiste, Leonie.","French: from Old French <i>corbeil</i> ‘basket’ (from Late Latin <i>corbicula</i>, a diminutive of <i>corbis</i> ‘basket’), a metonymic occupational name for a maker and seller of baskets, or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word because of a depression in the ground. Alternatively, a nickname derived from Old French <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ (see   Corp  ). Compare   Curby   and   Kirby  .","Altered form of French (mainly Loire-Atlantique) <b>Gourbil</b>, a surname which is most likely derived from the same Old French words <i>corbeil</i> ‘basket’ or <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ as the name in 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Curby","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Corbeil  .","English: variant of   Corby  ."]},{"name":"Corp","meanings":["English (mainly Somerset): in the southwest from Old French <i>corp</i> ‘raven’, probably applied as a nickname for someone with glossy dark hair. In northern and eastern (Scandinavian-influenced) counties the name may alternatively be derived from the cognate Old Norse <i>korpr</i>.","French: nickname from Old French <i>corp</i> ‘raven’ (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Bouchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Michel, Normand, Pierre, Cecile, Gilles, Lucien, Alphonse, Jacques, Alain.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Burchard</i>, composed of the elements <i>burg</i> ‘protection’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’.","French: in some cases, possibly also a nickname for someone with a big mouth (in either a literal or figurative sense), from <i>bouche</i> ‘mouth’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i>. Compare   Buschor  ,   Bushard  ,   Bushaw  , and   Bushor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bushard","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Bouchard  .","Possibly, in some cases, also an Americanized form of German <b>Buschard</b> (see   Bushart   2)."]},{"name":"Buschor","meanings":["Swiss German: probably a Germanized form of French   Bouchard  . Compare   Buschur   and   Bushor  ."]},{"name":"Bushore","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Bouchard  , reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. Compare   Bushor  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bouchard de Corbeil II was born in 1024, in Corbeil, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France, his father, Rainaud de Corbeil, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Rainaud de Corbeil, was 27. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Countess Adélaïde De Crécy. He died in 1095, in his hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1024–1095":"1024–1095","1027–1104":"1027–1104","1048–1104":"1048–1104","1050–1087":"1050–1087","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1072–1127":"1072–1127","0997–Male":"0997–Surnud","0998–Female":"0998–Surnud","about 1050":"umbes 1050","1087":"1087","14 August 1087":"14. august 1087","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1072":"1072","0997":"0997","1127":"1127","11